# {{wikipedia}}{{lb|en|typography}} The [[punctuation]] [[mark]] ⟨<span style="font-size: 2em;">[[,]]</span>⟩ [[use]]d to [[indicate]] a set of [[part]]s of a [[sentence]] or between [[element]]s of a [[list]].
#: {{syn|en|scratch comma|virgule|virgula|q3=in its obsolete form as a slash|come|id4=typography|q4=in its obsolete form as a middot|comma-point|q5=obsolete}}
#: {{hypo|en|comma of Didymus|inverted comma|Oxford comma|serial comma|syntonic comma}}
#* '''1828''', Richard Thomson, [https://books.google.co.jp/books?id=IyUNAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover ''Illustrations of the History of Great Britain'', Vol. II], [https://books.google.co.jp/books?id=IyUNAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA145 pp. 145–6]:
#*: No points were used by the ancient printers, excepting the [[colon]] and the [[period]]; but, after some time, a short [[oblique stroke]], called a [[virgil]], was introduced, which answered to the modern [[comma]]. In the fifteenth century this punctuation was improved by the famous Aldus Manutius with the typographical art in general; when he gave a better shape to the [[comma]], added the [[semicolon]], and assigned to the former points more proper places.
# {{lb|en|Romanian|_|typography}} A [[similar]]-[[looking]] [[subscript]] [[diacritical mark]].
# {{lb|en|entomology}} Any of various [[nymphalid]] butterflies of the genus ''[[Polygonia]]'', having a comma-shaped white mark on the underwings, especially {{taxlink|Polygonia c-album|species|ver=190708}} and {{taxlink|Polygonia c-aureum|species|ver=190708}} of North Africa, Europe, and Asia.
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Scott Shalaway|chapter=Close-ups| title=Butterflies in the Backyard| location=Mechanicsburg, Pa.| publisher={{w|Stackpole Books}}| year=2004| page=18| pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=xCTEEFCsaEcC&pg=PA18| isbn=978-0-8117-2695-5| passage='''Commas''' (''Polygonia comma'') and Question Marks (''Polygonia interrogationis'') occur from the Gulf Coast to Canada and west to the Rockies. [...] Question Marks and '''Commas''' are handsome butterflies with burnt orange and black markings. [...] On the underside of each hind wing of the '''Comma''' is a small, distinctive silver hook that resembles a comma.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Ann Simpson|author2=Rob Simpson|chapter=Butterflies and Moths|title=Nature Guide to Shenandoah National Park| series=Falcon Pocket Guide| location=Guilford, Conn.; Helena, Mont.| publisher=Falcon Guides, {{w|Globe Pequot Press}}| year=2013| page=91| pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=rnZBBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA91| isbn=978-0-7627-7076-2| passage=Other members of this genus that are frequently encountered in the park are the eastern '''comma''' (''P. comma'') and question mark (''P. interrogationis'').}}
# {{lb|en|music}} A difference in the calculation of nearly identical [[interval]]s by different ways.
# {{lb|en|genetics}} A [[delimit]]ing [[marker]] between items in a [[genetic]] [[sequence]].
# {{lb|en|rhetoric}} In [[Ancient Greek]] [[rhetoric]], a short clause, something less than a colon, originally denoted by comma marks. In antiquity it was defined as a combination of words having no more than eight syllables in all. It was later applied to longer phrases, e.g. the {{w|Johannine comma}}.
# {{lb|en|figurative}} A [[brief]] [[interval]].

